// ── Can and Can't ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

#section-header("Can and Can't")

You have no attributes or dice. Everything different from an average human
is on your "can and can't" list.

*Can and can't are absolute.* If you _can_, nothing will prevent it.
If you _can't_, nothing will allow it. The rules seem strict --- that's what
makes the game fun.

No danger kills you suddenly. The GM always gives you the picture, your
options, and signals how well things are going.
*Pay close attention to those signals.*

// ── Fear ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

#section-header("Fear")

Fear happens when you:

#rule-item[See humans dying.]
#rule-item[Are being hunted.]
#rule-item[See the supernatural.]
#rule-item[Risk your own life willingly.]

Each fear event *crosses off one of your can/can't* (good or bad) until
you get a safe night's sleep. At first this can strengthen you --- you
probably cross the bad traits first. But fear keeps building.

// ── Snapping ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

#section-header("Snapping")

When you cross the *third* can/can't, you must add a *condition* to one
ability that has no condition yet (i.e. one with an "if" or "when").
After that, all fear clears and you recover all your can/can'ts.

A condition can be:

#rule-item[*An object* you can lose --- a hat, a book, a gun, a pendant. (If it's
  tied to your body, losing it will also cost you a finger.)]

#rule-item[*An indulging activity* --- smoking, drinking, praying, sex. Something
  you could run out of or be forced to skip.]

#rule-item[*A mannerism* --- snapping your fingers, the sign of the cross, kissing
  a ring. Something you, the player, could forget to say you're doing.]

If *all* your can/can'ts already have a condition, you *snap* --- you see
the world differently and gain one new can/can't (something slightly
supernatural or just above the human peak).

Optionally, when snapping you may instead *remove a condition* by
dropping one of your can'ts permanently.

Keep new can/can'ts aligned with your character's profile and motto.

// ── Playing Diceless ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

#section-header("Playing Diceless")

*Ask what your character thinks.* You don't have your character's skills.
If they're an expert brawler, ask "do I think we can handle him?" --- the
GM will give you an honest picture. If they're an investigator, ask
"what do I think is worth noting here?" and the GM will point you in the
right direction.

*Pay attention to damage.* Damage is the GM telling you that what you're
doing isn't working. Your character won't die from a sudden explosion
without warning --- but they might die fighting a stronger opponent alone
while ignoring the mounting injuries. When the GM says "the rocks are
getting bigger," change course fast. Some situations have no clean exit
--- choosing the lesser evil is a big part of this game.

